post_text:
MYTH: Personal information in the Census is shared with other government agencies.
FACT: Your personal information is kept confidential. The Census Bureau is bound by federal law to protect your information, and your data is used only for statistical purposes. (source: https://2020census.gov/en/data-protection.html)

There's more than a trillion dollars at stake! Take 10 minutes. It will impact us for ten years. #mcsdwe #keepgalearning #census2020
shared_text:
Georgia Department of Education
September 8 at 9:50 PM ¬∑

To support Georgia's public schools, fill out your 2020 Census!

We need a complete count in the Census to ensure full funding for programs like the National School Lunch program, IDEA special education funding, and Title I grants -- and right now, Georgia is lagging behind other states for response rate.

To fill out your Census, visit my2020census.gov or call 844-330-2020 (English) or 844-468-2020 (Espa√±ol). If you have received a paper form, you can complete and mail it at any time.

post_text: Fact: The U.S. Census Bureau uses the data you submit for the Census to draw legislative districts. If we are under counted, we are potentially underrepresented. Our representation in the House of Representatives depends on you! #columbuscounts #mcsdwe
shared_text:
Columbus Counts 2020
August 29 at 10:00 PM ¬∑

The results of this once-a-decade count determine the number of seats each state has in the House of Representatives. The data is used to draw congressional and state legislative districts. Political districts at the federal, state and local levels are drawn based on population data. So, without an accurate count, it is impossible to ensure that people‚Äôs votes will have the same weight. ‚öñÔ∏èüèõ

Georgia State Representative Calvin Smyre, District 135, wants YOU to complete the 2020 Census! Rep. Smyre knows how urgent it is for us to make Columbus count. Learn more and fill out the Census now by visiting www.2020census.gov. ‚úÖ

post_text: Our students are amazing! Each student at Lonnie Jackson Academy sent handmade cards to the rangers of Parks Victoria in Kew, Australia. Listen to the heartfelt message they sent back. #mcsdwe
shared_text:
Parks Victoria
March 4 at 12:25 AM ¬∑

We recently received a box of beautiful handmade cards from the Lonnie Jackson Academy in Georgia, USA.

The kids in each class made colourful cards to thank Parks Victoria's rangers for their hard work in putting out fires and looking after the environment. We took the cards on a road trip so that rangers could read them. Watch the video to see what happened.

THANKS SO MUCH :) Your cards made so many people smile.

post_text: Congratulations to our inaugural Muscogee Educational Excellence Foundation Harvard Fellows Buntin Scholars!
shared_text:
Muscogee Educational Excellence Foundation
March 3 at 10:30 PM ¬∑

HUGE. NEWS!
Thanks to some very generous community members, MEEF is proud to introduce the Harvard Fellow Buntin Scholars. Named in honor of former MCSD Superintendent Jim Buntin, these Harvard Fellows Buntin Scholars come from high poverty schools with the mission of helping attack poverty in Muscogee County starting in the classroom. We are in awe of what our community can do when it sees a need - and how they rally to support these exceptional teachers!

Marquette McRae McKnight. Judy Thomas Lorie-Warren Steele, Janet Davis Linda Hitz Shinkle Tish Buntin Shirley Stefan Lawrence Christine Hull Shane Larkin

IMPORTANT: We will continue to provide updates related to COVID-19. At this time, there are no confirmed cases in our schools or community. However, we follow the emergency preparedness plans, specific to K-12 schools, as directed by the Georgia Department of Education, Georgia Department of Public Health, and CDC.

Learn more: http://bit.ly/2Ilob8C
shared_text:
Georgia Department of Education
March 3 at 9:02 PM ¬∑

We are working closely with the Office of the Governor, the Georgia Department of Public Health and other agencies to ensure local school districts, parents, and students have the most accurate and up-to-date information regarding COVID-19 (commonly called coronavirus).

Regarding school closures: we are following the direction of the Georgia Department of Public Health, and advising local school districts to follow the direction of their local board of health. At this time, DPH has advised us that students who are not ill can safely attend schools. We are in regular contact with DPH and will immediately inform school districts if their recommendation changes.

For more information and answers to frequently asked questions, click here: https://www.gadoe.org/External-Affairs-and-Policy/communications/Pages/coronavirus.aspx

HEADS UP! There are no cases of the Coronavirus Disease 2019, now referred to as COVID-19, in Georgia. However, the Georgia Department of Public Health and Centers For Disease Control CDC recommend the following actions to prevent the spread of germs:
-Stay home when you are sick with respiratory disease symptoms.
-Cover coughs and sneezes with a tissue, then throw it in the trash can.
-Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds; especially after going to the bathroom; before eating; and after blowing your nose, coughing, or sneezing.
If soap and water are not readily available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer with 60%-95% alcohol.
-Routinely clean frequently touched surfaces and objects.
shared_text:
Georgia Department of Public Health
March 1 at 4:55 PM ¬∑

To protect yourself from #COVID19, the same measures that are urged to prevent the spread of any respiratory virus are increasingly important for all Georgians:

- Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer.
- Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth with unwashed hands.
- Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
- Stay home when you are sick.
https://dph.georgia.gov

post_text: Let's hear it for our teacher cadets at Blackmon Road Middle School! #mcsdwe
shared_text:
Blackmon Road Middle School
February 27 at 7:37 PM ¬∑

Teacher Cadets at Blackmon Road Middle School is a club for students that are interested in teaching as a career choice. Blackmon Road is the only Middle School in Muscogee County that offers this club to its students. Throughout the year, Teacher Cadets work on a Lesson Plan designed for a 2nd grade class. They choose the standard, and use their imagination to plan the perfect lesson. This year, five teams competed in the first round of teaching. Three teams were chosen by the Columbus State University judges to compete in the final round of teaching at North Columbus Elementary School ‚Ä™on Monday, March 9.‚Ä¨ The cadets that made it to the final round at North Columbus Elementary are: Ansley Jankiewicz, Olivia Oyster, Angela Li, Annalise McCann, Abby Harp, and Ava Perez.

post_text: Congratulations to Midland Middle School's eighth-grade student SuhasTadiparthi for winning the Muscogee County School District spelling bee! The winning word was "marionette." Aaron Cohn Middle School student, Owen Steele, is the second-place winner and Blanchard Elementary School student, Edward Boughner, came in third place. Great job to all of the participants! (Pictured left to right: Darryl Carter, Suhas Tadiparthi, Owen Steele, Edward Boughner, and Dr. Lewis)
